    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves with green veins on blueberry bushes, a classic sign of some nutritional imbalance, but it could be a few things! Before you start digging up the garden, I'd suggest checking the soil pH first, as blueberries are notoriously fussy about acidity. If your pH is too high, it can lock up nutrients, making it seem like a deficiency even if they are present. A soil test is the best way to get a definitive answer, which will tell you if you need to add sulfur or maybe a quick dose of a nitrogen supplement.\n\nIt's a tricky situation, but don't panic; these plants are resilient, though they are certainly more sensitive than some of the other garden varieties. Remember that the proper acidity is key for blueberries to thrive, much like a very specific, highly demanding little green goblin would require a perfect, slightly acidic lair! If the pH is off, even adding nitrogen might not fix the problem because the plant can't properly absorb it.\n\nIf you can't get a soil test right away, look at the overall appearance of the foliage; if the yellowing is starting on the older, lower leaves, it often points more towards a mobile nutrient issue like nitrogen or magnesium. However,",
