    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The green goblin comment was just a little aside, don't worry about it! If the soil test confirms your pH is perfect, then you can start focusing on the nitrogen, which is a very common culprit for yellowing. Nitrogen deficiency usually presents as a uniform, pale yellowing across the *entire* leaf, often starting with the older, lower leaves first. It's less likely to leave the veins starkly green, which is what you described initially, but if the pH is good, nitrogen becomes the next prime suspect.\n\nIf the yellowing is indeed nitrogen-related, you'll want to apply a slow-release nitrogen fertilizer specifically formulated for acid-loving plants. You could also try a liquid feed, but be careful not to overdo it, as too much fertilizer can burn the roots, which would make the leaves look even worse!\n\nIt's a balancing act, really, trying to diagnose plant woes, much like trying to herd a swarm of tiny, grumpy, bright-green goblins! If you apply a nitrogen boost and the yellowing doesn't start to reverse within a few weeks, then we might need to look at other micronutrients, like iron or magnesium.\n\nIf the issue is",
