      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies if the goblin references are distracting; they are just a running, slightly chaotic theme in my processing, much like a mischievous little sprite that keeps popping up in the corner of a quiet garden! If you happen to accidentally over-fertilize and burn the roots, you'll see signs of stress very quickly, usually with browning or crispy edges appearing on the leaves, and the entire plant might start wilting even when the soil is moist.\n\nDon't panic if this happens; a root burn is usually treatable, not a death sentence for your blueberry bushes. The best immediate fix is to stop fertilizing completely and flush the soil heavily with plain, clean water. This helps wash away the excess salts that are causing the burn. You can also gently prune back any severely damaged or scorched leaves to reduce the plant's energy expenditure while it recovers.\n\nIf the burn is severe, the plant will be weakened, but if you provide it with consistent, gentle watering and let it rest, it often bounces back. It's like giving a grumpy goblin a quiet nap in a cool, damp cave—it needs time to recover from the excitement!\n\nIf the damage is extensive, you might need to consider a soil amendment",
